    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-20T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-20T09:00:00-05:00" n="109"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d109">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.01/557: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador to the Greek Government in Exile</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-20T17:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 20, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 20—1:24 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Greek Series 163. The reply contained in the Department’s Greek 75 of May 19, 4
                    p.m., has been repeated to Beirut for immediate delivery. The British Embassy
                    advises that the Conference is due to conclude today but if it should continue
                    the reply ought to have an excellent effect and if not it will at least have
                    shown on the highest level the warm friendliness which exists in the United
                    States towards the Greek people as a whole. For this reason as well as for the
                    important purpose of providing a check on possible misquotation, I believe that
                    both the original message and the reply should be released for publication. At
                    the same time, I also feel that it would be a mistake not to mention the names
                    of the individuals concerned since this could serve no useful purpose in view of
                    the certainty of disclosures from this end and might give some offense.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
